---
/**
 * Cedar — combined explainer (left) + live "Ask Cedar" chat (right).
 * The chat sits where empty space used to be on this section so a
 * visitor reading about Cedar can immediately try it without scrolling
 * to a separate Q&A surface.
 */
import '../styles/cedar.css';
import IconUpload from './icons/IconUpload.astro';
import IconSurfaceAssumption from './icons/IconSurfaceAssumption.astro';
import IconSourceRecord from './icons/IconSourceRecord.astro';
import FAQSection from './FAQSection.astro';
---
<section class="cedar-about" id="cedar">
  <div class="cedar-about__inner">
    <div class="cedar-about__left">
      <p class="cedar-about__byline">Cedar</p>
      <h2 class="cedar-about__lede">
        AI for the unglamorous parts of economic impact analysis.
      </h2>
      <p class="cedar-about__intro">
        Cedar is the Lumecon AI. It reads messy data, explains what's happening and why while you stay in control, and reshapes the study for whichever audience you're talking to next.
      </p>
      <p class="cedar-about__body">
        Cedar is RAG-based, so the answers come from your actual files and the source record. Every assumption surfaces for your sign-off before it's used. The team handled PII and sensitive government data at the Federal Reserve and other federal agencies, so Cedar is built for the data that matters.
      </p>
      <p class="cedar-about__body">
        Cedar is also the way in for organizations that haven't used AI yet. The model is a thought partner. You're still the author. Governments, ministries, and mission-driven teams that have to be careful about model use can adopt Cedar without ceding the call on what the study actually says.
      </p>
      <ol class="cedar-steps" aria-label="What Cedar does">
        <li class="cedar-step">
          <details class="cedar-step__details">
            <summary class="cedar-step__summary">
              <span class="cedar-step__icon"><IconUpload /></span>
              <span class="cedar-step__num">01</span>
              <h3 class="cedar-step__head">Works with the data you actually have</h3>
              <span class="cedar-step__chev" aria-hidden="true"></span>
            </summary>
            <p class="cedar-step__body">Budgets, payroll detail, council agendas, board reports, audits, grant filings. Cedar pulls structure out of whatever your departments can send, in whatever shape it arrives.</p>
          </details>
        </li>
        <li class="cedar-step">
          <details class="cedar-step__details">
            <summary class="cedar-step__summary">
              <span class="cedar-step__icon"><IconSurfaceAssumption /></span>
              <span class="cedar-step__num">02</span>
              <h3 class="cedar-step__head">Explains what's happening, and why</h3>
              <span class="cedar-step__chev" aria-hidden="true"></span>
            </summary>
            <p class="cedar-step__body">Every multiplier, regional bridge, and base-year choice is named before it's used, with a one-line rationale. You confirm or override. The audit trail builds itself as the study runs.</p>
          </details>
        </li>
        <li class="cedar-step">
          <details class="cedar-step__details">
            <summary class="cedar-step__summary">
              <span class="cedar-step__icon"><IconSourceRecord /></span>
              <span class="cedar-step__num">03</span>
              <h3 class="cedar-step__head">Reshapes the study for any audience</h3>
              <span class="cedar-step__chev" aria-hidden="true"></span>
            </summary>
            <p class="cedar-step__body">Council meeting, grant filing, board memo, public release. The same result, redrawn for whoever asked the question. No copying numbers between five different decks.</p>
          </details>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </div>
    <aside class="cedar-about__right" aria-label="Ask Cedar">
      <FAQSection compact={true} />
    </aside>
  </div>
</section>
